I was very few attempts at kleptoparasitism, possibly suggesting that fish were abundant and easy to catch.

There were huge numbers of piscivorous birds along the western edge of the lake (rather than in the middle of the lake), with many mergansers, Bald Eagles, and gulls seen with fish. Five Gadwalls were the only dabbling ducks.

TRIP COMMENTS: Highest number of CLGR ever here. Unid''ed numbered an add''l 200 birds.--Heermann''s gull on peninsula outer end of Conn Cr. Adult. black-tipped orange bill, blackish head, dark grey wings and mantle, grey un''parts, black legs/feet; white tipped black tail. small incursion of this species inland since 10/31-11/2 storms, including 2 birds at Clear L. at this time. 1st Napa Co record. 2 BGGN wintered here, 2007-08. CCSP at open west part of north shore road. Separated from CHSP by plain light-colored lores, buff auriculars with broad darker bordering post-oc and ''moustache;'' bright buffy breast; ''daintier'' aspect to head with ''softer'' facial expression. 1st county record. SOSPs included a couple ''morphna'' types. fair/high overcast (0830-), 0-5 w, 38-66.

This was a large bird of prey with a conspicuously large head, a moderately long neck, and a rather massive and strongly hooked bill.  The wings were long and parallel-sided with the wingtips formed by elongate primaries.  The flight profile appeared quite flat.  The tail was also moderately long and slightly rounded at the tip.  The head was mostly whitish yet with a conspicuous dark auricular-patch and fine dark streaking throughout.  I was a bit surprised that this bird was extensively white below with the throat and breast apparently blackish but the rest of the underparts mostly white yet with relatively bold, dark streaking.  The underwing coverts were also extensively white but with some dark mottling, and the undersides of the remiges were mostly dark.  The upperparts and uppersides of the wings were mostly dark brown but there was a large but diffuse patch of creamy white in the center of the upper back and some pale mottling on the coverts.  The upperside of the tail was mostly dark but there seemed to be some pale mottling (though no tail band).  I failed to note the color of the eyes, but the bill was extensively yellow and the legs and feet were also bright yellow.
